In [[Canada]], the '''Office of the Custodian of Enemy Property''', attached to the [[Secretary of State for Canada]],{{sfn|Roberts-Moore|1986|p=95}} was established in 1916 and existed until 1985, dealing with the property of [[Military history of Canada|Canada's enemies in both World Wars]] as well as with the seized property of [[Japanese Canadians]].
==History== ===1916-1939=== The office of Custodian was originally created in 1916, during the [[First World War]], deriving its authority from the ''[[War Measures Act]]'' and the ''Consolidated Orders Respecting Trading with the Enemy'',<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= May 6, 1916|title= Supplement: P.C. 1023|url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/databases/canada-gazette/093/001060-119.01-e.php?document_id_nbr=6215&f=p|journal= [[Canada Gazette]]|pages= 1-11}}</ref> and its functions included the seizure and liquidation of enemy property. This followed the adoption of the UK [[trading with the enemy]] restrictions enacted in 1914,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue= 28862|date= 4 August 1914|page= 6166|supp= 2|title=A Proclamation Relating to Trading with the Enemy}}</ref><ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title =Trading with the Enemy Act, 1914|abbr =|year =1914|chapter =87 (UK)|link=https://archive.org/stream/actsofparl191415v01cana#page/n218/mode/1up}}</ref> which had been incorporated into Canadian law in 1914 by [[order in council]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= October 30, 1914|title= Extra: P.C. 2724|url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/databases/canada-gazette/093/001060-119.01-e.php?document_id_nbr=14572&f=p|journal= [[Canada Gazette]]|pages= 2-3}}</ref> From 1916 to 1919, the [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]] and the Secretary of State had joint responsibility for acting as Custodian.{{sfn|Roberts-Moore|1986|p=96}}
From 1920 to 1939, it served the function of administering war claims and reparations. Under legislation authorizing the conclusion of treaties of peace<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title =The Treaties of Peace Act, 1919|abbr =S.C.|year =1919 (2nd Sess.)|chapter =30|link=https://archive.org/stream/actsofparl1919v01cana_0#page/81/mode/1up}}</ref> the ''Treaty of Peace (Germany) Order, 1920'' was issued to create the Office,<ref>[https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/politics-government/orders-council/Pages/item.aspx?IdNumber=392695 P.C. 755] (April 14, 1920)</ref> under the authority of the Secretary of State as sold custodian.{{sfn|Roberts-Moore|1986|p=96}} The Office acted as one of the "clearing offices" authorized under Article 296 of the [[Treaty of Versailles]] for the collection and payment of enemy debts,{{sfn|Roberts-Moore|1986|p=96}} and Article 297 authorized Canada to keep and liquidate any German property in Canada.{{sfn|Roberts-Moore|1986|p=98}} Investigations and recommendations respecting claims for reparations were undertaken by the separately appointed [[Royal Commission on Reparations]], chaired by [[Errol McDougall]].{{sfn|Roberts-Moore|1986|p=98}}
===1939-1985=== With the outbreak of the [[Second World War]], the ''Regulations respecting Trading with the Enemy, 1939'' expanded the scope of the Office.<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= September 11, 1939|title= Extra: P.C. 2512|url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/databases/canada-gazette/093/001060-119.01-e.php?document_id_nbr=8325&f=p|journal= [[Canada Gazette]]|pages= 1-15}}</ref> From 1942 the role of the Custodian was expanded to include the administration of property seized from [[Japanese Canadians]].
In the postwar period, the Custodian had the responsibility for resolving Canadian War Claims, and the resolution of outstanding wartime property issues. This latter process was complicated by the implications of the large scale nationalization of property in [[Eastern Europe]] by the Communist regimes established in the post war period under Soviet auspices. The WWII regulations were continued on a temporary basis following the end of hostilities, and were continued in 1947 by the ''Trading with the Enemy (Transitional Powers) Act''.<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title =The Trading with the Enemy (Transitional Powers) Act|abbr =S.C.|year =1947|chapter =24|link=https://archive.org/stream/actsofparl1947v01cana#page/138/mode/2up}}</ref> The Act ceased to have effect at the end of September 1992,<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= October 21, 1992|title= SI/92-192: Proclamation Declaring that the Act shall Continue in Force until September 30, 1992|url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/databases/canada-gazette/093/001060-119.01-e.php?document_id_nbr=14904&f=p|journal= [[Canada Gazette]]|volume= 126|issue= 22|pages= 4076-4077}}</ref> and was consequently repealed in 1996.<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title =Department of Public Works and Government Services Act|abbr =S.C.|year =1996|chapter =16|section=66|link=https://archive.org/stream/actsofparl1996v01cana#page/n519/mode/1up}}</ref>
The Office ceased operations in 1985. Its files were transferred to [[Library and Archives Canada]], but there is evidence that some have been destroyed without assessing their historical value.{{sfn|Roberts-Moore|1986|p=100}} The Office never produced [[annual report]]s outlining its activities.{{sfn|Roberts-Moore|1986|p=95}}
==See also== * [[Custodian of Enemy Property]] * [[Japanese Canadian Internment]]
==Further reading== ===Academic analysis=== * {{cite journal |last1= Roberts-Moore|first1= Judith|date= 1986|title= The Office of the Custodian of Enemy Property: An Overview of the Office and its Records, 1920-1952|url= https://archivaria.ca/index.php/archivaria/article/view/11304/12244|journal= Archivaria|issue= 22|pages= 95-106|issn=1923-6409|ref=harv}} ===Reports of the Royal Commission on Reparations=== * {{cite book |author=Errol M. McDougall, Commissioner |title= Reparations 1930-1931: Interim Report|url= http://publications.gc.ca/collections/collection_2016/bcp-pco/Z1-1930-1-eng.pdf|location= Ottawa|publisher=King's Printer|date= 1931}} * {{cite book |author=Errol M. McDougall, Commissioner |title= Reparations 1930-1931: Report, Maltreatment of Prisoners of War|url= http://publications.gc.ca/collections/collection_2016/bcp-pco/Z1-1930-4-1-eng.pdf|location= Ottawa|publisher=King's Printer|date= 1932}} * {{cite book |author=Errol M. McDougall, Commissioner |title= Reparations 1932-1933: Final Report|volume=1|url= http://publications.gc.ca/collections/collection_2016/bcp-pco/Z1-1930-6-1-eng.pdf|location= Ottawa|publisher=King's Printer|date= 1933}} * {{cite book |author=Errol M. McDougall, Commissioner |title= Reparations 1932-1933: Final Report|volume=2|url= http://publications.gc.ca/collections/collection_2016/bcp-pco/Z1-1930-6-2-eng.pdf|location= Ottawa|publisher=King's Printer|date= 1933}}
